[2]
Date: 4 Apr 2013
From: Merritt Clifton [edited]
<anmlpepl@whidbey.com>


Pigeons ARE poultry in China. Nowhere in the coverage is there any hint that the pigeons in question are wild and free-flying, and in 3 visits to various parts of China, I have seen very few pigeons who were not either poultry (most of them) or domestic flocks used in pigeon-racing competitions.

Pigeon-flying is relatively big in China, but much of the habitat is not very favorable to large concentrations of wild pigeons as we know them in the USA. Beijing, for example, is famous for hosting huge numbers of raptors, who hunt pigeons, mice, rats, etc.

The Beijing Raptor Center, one of the most eminent raptor research and rehabilitation facilities in the world, is at Beijing University, right in the middle of the city. Most of their field work is done right within the city limits, because that's where the hawks, owls, and eagles are.

The incredible mixing of species in Chinese live markets might have a great deal to do with H7N9 spreading from whatever the original host species, just as it did with SARS. Here "poultry" means basically chickens, ducks, and geese. In China, besides those 3 species, practically every live market also includes pigeons, quail, pheasants, guinea fowl, and sometimes peafowl, and right next door you'll have open-air pet markets selling captive songbirds, many of them illegally caught from the wild.

