[3]
Date: 5 Apr 2013
Source: N3ews.com.au
http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/world/china-reports-fifth-h7n9-bird-flu-death/story-e6frfkui-1226612916941


All Shanghai markets closed
---------------------------
Shanghai has ordered all live poultry markets in the city closed after culling more than 20 000 birds to curb the spread of the H7N9 flu virus, which has killed 6 people in China. The latest fatality was a 64-year-old farmer who died in Huzhou, in the eastern province of Zhejiang, local officials said on Friday [5 Apr 2013], according to the state Xinhua news agency. He is thought to be among 14 previously confirmed human cases of H7N9 virus infection and is the 2nd person from Zhejiang province to die from the new bird flu strain, with the other 4 fatalities in Shanghai, China's commercial hub.

Shanghai has a population of 23 million people, and city government spokesman Xu Wei said its live poultry markets were being shuttered temporarily for "public safety" purposes, and all trade in live poultry banned.

The moves came after the virus was found in samples from a pigeon from the Huhuai market in Shanghai, where Xinhua said a total of 20 536 chickens, ducks, geese, and pigeons had been slaughtered. On Friday [5 Apr 2013], the entrance to the poultry section was concealed with wooden boards and sealed off with plastic tape, with a police car parked nearby and white disinfectant powder sprinkled in the street. Two staff members at the market told Agence France-Presse that slaughter was completed overnight, but one of them added: "Of course, I'm worried."

